Report: The malware uses an XOR-based routine to decode hard-coded strings before use and re-encodes them afterward to hinder static analysis.
It displays a fake certificate installation progress bar window to make the activity appear benign to the user.
While the progress bar is shown on the UI thread, the core malicious logic is executed in a separate worker thread.
It drops two certificate files with random names and a .crt extension into the %TEMP% directory.
It uses certutil.exe to import the dropped certificate files into the local Root and CA certificate stores.
It locates the Firefox installation directory by enumerating the file system for the Firefox browser path.
It ensures the Firefox defaults/pref directory structure exists by creating any missing subdirectories under the installation path.
It creates the wincerts.js file under the Firefox defaults/pref directory and prepares it for writing configuration data.
It writes a preference line that enables Firefox to trust Windows system root certificates, thereby trusting the malicious root certificate that was installed.
It creates a new local user account named "UpdatusUser" with the password "admQ!23" on the compromised system.
It adds the UpdatusUser account to the BUILTIN\Administrators group to grant the attacker full administrative privileges.

It modifies specific registry keys under Winlogon, LSA, and policies\system to hide the account and adjust local account access, then collects IP and MAC information from all network interfaces and sends it with an error code to a remote /registered HTTP endpoint.
